## Analysis: `getEmittedH` and `-femit-h` (emit-h) in Zig master (0.16.0-dev)

**Bottom line: `emit-h` is officially broken in the current master branch.** The `getEmittedH` function exists in the build system layer, passes the `-femit-h` flag to the compiler, but the compiler-side implementation is intentionally short-circuited with a `if (true) return;` guard comment. Here is the full picture:

---

### 1. `getEmittedH` in [`lib/std/Build/Step/Compile.zig`](https://github.com/ziglang/zig/blob/master/lib/std/Build/Step/Compile.zig#L897-L902)

```zig
/// Returns the path to the generated header file.
/// This function can only be called for libraries or objects.
pub fn getEmittedH(compile: *Compile) LazyPath {
    assert(compile.kind != .exe and compile.kind != .@"test");
    return compile.getEmittedFileGeneric(&compile.generated_h);
}
```

**What it does:**
- It takes a `*Compile` step (which must be a `lib` or `obj` kind — it asserts and panics otherwise)
- It lazily allocates a `GeneratedFile` for `compile.generated_h` and returns a `LazyPath` pointing to it
- `getEmittedFileGeneric` is a helper shared by all `getEmitted*` functions — it just creates the `GeneratedFile` slot if not already created

**Is it deprecated?** No — unlike many other functions in the same file that are marked `/// Deprecated; use ... instead. /// To be removed after 0.15.0 is tagged`, `getEmittedH` carries **no deprecation notice**.

---

### 2. How it wires into the build pipeline

When `generated_h` is non-null, the `getZigArgs` function (which constructs the CLI arguments for the `zig` compiler subprocess) passes the `-femit-h` flag at [line 1505](https://github.com/ziglang/zig/blob/master/lib/std/Build/Step/Compile.zig#L1499-L1505):

```zig
if (compile.generated_asm != null) try zig_args.append("-femit-asm");
if (compile.generated_bin == null) try zig_args.append("-fno-emit-bin");
if (compile.generated_docs != null) try zig_args.append("-femit-docs");
if (compile.generated_implib != null) try zig_args.append("-femit-implib");
if (compile.generated_llvm_bc != null) try zig_args.append("-femit-llvm-bc");
if (compile.generated_llvm_ir != null) try zig_args.append("-femit-llvm-ir");
if (compile.generated_h != null) try zig_args.append("-femit-h");  // ← this line
```

After the compiler runs, `make()` wires the output path back via [line 1893](https://github.com/ziglang/zig/blob/master/lib/std/Build/Step/Compile.zig#L1889-L1897):

```zig
if (compile.generated_bin)     |lp| lp.path = compile.outputPath(output_dir, .bin);
if (compile.generated_pdb)     |lp| lp.path = compile.outputPath(output_dir, .pdb);
if (compile.generated_implib)  |lp| lp.path = compile.outputPath(output_dir, .implib);
if (compile.generated_h)       |lp| lp.path = compile.outputPath(output_dir, .h);  // ← this line
// ...
```

So the build system infrastructure **is fully wired up** — `getEmittedH` → `-femit-h` flag → path populated after build. The breakage lives entirely inside the compiler.

---

### 3. The actual breakage: `if (true) return;` in [`src/link/C.zig`](https://github.com/ziglang/zig/blob/master/src/link/C.zig#L759-L763)

```zig
pub fn flushEmitH(zcu: *Zcu) !void {
    const tracy = trace(@src());
    defer tracy.end();

    if (true) return; // emit-h is regressed

    const emit_h = zcu.emit_h orelse return;
    // ... dead code: the actual header-writing logic follows
```

This is the `flushEmitH` function in the C linker backend. It is the **single function responsible for writing the `.h` file to disk**, and it is **completely no-opped** with the comment `// emit-h is regressed`. The rest of the function (iterating `emit_h.decl_table`, gathering buffers, writing with `pwritevAll`) is unreachable dead code.

This function is called from [`src/Compilation.zig`](https://github.com/ziglang/zig/blob/master/src/Compilation.zig):

```zig
if (comp.zcu) |zcu| {
    try link.File.C.flushEmitH(zcu);
}
```

So even though the flag reaches the compiler, it silently does nothing.

---

### 4. The `InstallArtifact` integration is also commented out

In [`lib/std/Build/Step/InstallArtifact.zig`](https://github.com/ziglang/zig/blob/master/lib/std/Build/Step/InstallArtifact.zig#L109-L113):

```zig
if (install_artifact.dest_dir != null) install_artifact.emitted_bin = artifact.getEmittedBin();
if (install_artifact.pdb_dir != null) install_artifact.emitted_pdb = artifact.getEmittedPdb();
// https://github.com/ziglang/zig/issues/9698
//if (install_artifact.h_dir != null) install_artifact.emitted_h = artifact.getEmittedH();
if (install_artifact.implib_dir != null) install_artifact.emitted_implib = artifact.getEmittedImplib();
```

The `InstallArtifact` step — which normally wires up `getEmittedH()` automatically when you call `b.installArtifact()` — has that line **commented out** referencing [issue #9698](https://github.com/ziglang/zig/issues/9698). Even if you add `getEmittedH()` manually to your build script, the `.h_dir` install integration is disabled.

---

### 5. There is a guard at the `Compilation` configuration level too

In [`src/Compilation.zig`](https://github.com/ziglang/zig/blob/master/src/Compilation.zig), the enum for config-level errors includes:

```zig
emit_h_without_zcu,
// ...
.emit_h_without_zcu => try w.writeAll("cannot emit C header with no Zig source files"),
```

This means even before reaching `flushEmitH`, the configuration step will reject `-femit-h` for compilations with no Zig source (e.g., pure-C compilations), with a proper error message.

---

### Summary Table

| Layer | Status | Notes |
|---|---|---|
| `getEmittedH()` in `Compile.zig` | ✅ Present, not deprecated | Allocates `generated_h`, triggers `-femit-h` |
| `-femit-h` CLI arg sent to compiler | ✅ Working | `getZigArgs` emits it when `generated_h != null` |
| Output path wired after compilation | ✅ Present | `make()` calls `outputPath(output_dir, .h)` |
| `InstallArtifact` auto-install of `.h` | ❌ Commented out | References [issue #9698](https://github.com/ziglang/zig/issues/9698) |
| `flushEmitH()` in `link/C.zig` | ❌ **Broken** | `if (true) return; // emit-h is regressed` |
| Compiler-side header generation | ❌ **Dead code** | Unreachable past the `if (true) return` |

**Community reports are correct.** The feature has been in a regressed state (the comment says so explicitly in the source). The build system scaffolding is intact, but the compiler backend that would actually emit the `.h` file has been unconditionally short-circuited. Using `getEmittedH()` will complete the build without error but will silently **not produce a `.h` file**.
